  "prompt": "How do I submit a question?",
  "response": "It depends on where you're trying to submit a question!  Here's a breakdown based on common scenarios:\n\n**1. General Knowledge/Information Questions (like you're doing right now):**\n\n*   **You already are!** You're asking me, a large language model, a question. Just type your question in the text box.\n\n**2. Online Forums (e.g., Reddit, Stack Overflow, Quora):**\n\n*   **Find the appropriate subreddit/forum:**  Use the search function on the site to find the community most relevant to your question. For example, if you have a programming question, you might use Stack Overflow. For a question about cats, you might use a subreddit dedicated to cats.\n*   **Look for a \"Post Question,\" \"New Post,\" or similar button:**  This is usually prominently displayed on the main page of the forum or subreddit.\n*   **Create a clear and concise title:**  The title is the first thing people see, so make it informative and engaging.  Instead of \"Help me!\", try \"Python: How to sort a list of dictionaries by a specific key?\"\n*   **Provide context and details:**  Clearly explain what you're trying to achieve, what you've already tried, and what problems you're encountering.  The more information you provide, the easier it will be for others to help you.\n*   **Use proper formatting:**  Use headings, bullet points, and code blocks to make your question easy to read and understand.  Many forums use Markdown formatting.\n*   **Tag your question appropriately:**  Forums often have tags that help categorize questions.  Use relevant tags so the right people see your question.\n*   **Be respectful and polite:**  Remember that people are volunteering their time to help you.  Thank them for their assistance.\n\n**3. A Specific Company's Support System:**\n\n*   **Check their website for a \"Contact Us\" or \"Support\" page:** Most companies have a dedicated page for customer service.\n*   **Look for FAQs:** Often, the answer to your question may already be addressed.\n*   **Search their knowledge base:** Many companies have databases of articles and tutorials.\n*   **Use their online form:** Many companies provide a form to submit your question or issue.\n*   **Consider live chat or phone support:** If the issue is urgent, you might try these options.\n*   **Be prepared to provide:**\n    *   Your account information\n    *   A detailed description of your issue\n    *   Steps to reproduce the problem (if applicable)\n    *   Screenshots (if helpful)\n\n**4. Emailing a Question:**\n\n*   **Find the appropriate email address:** This might be a general \"info@\" address or a more specific one like \"support@\".\n*   **Write a clear and concise subject line:**  Make it specific to the topic of your question.\n*   **Introduce yourself (briefly):**  Especially if you're a customer.\n*   **Clearly state your question:**  Be specific and provide context.\n*   **Use proper grammar and spelling:**  This makes your email more professional and easier to understand.\n*   **Be polite and respectful:**  Thank them for their time and assistance.\n\n**5. Academic Setting (e.g., Asking a Professor/Teacher):**\n\n*   **Check the syllabus:**  The answer to your question might be there.\n*   **Attend office hours:**  This is a great way to get personalized help.\n*   **Formulate your question carefully:**  Think about what you're really asking.\n*   **Be specific:**  Don't just say \"I don't understand this.\"  Explain what you *don't* understand.\n*   **Show that you've tried to figure it out yourself:**  Mention what you've already tried.\n*   **Be respectful of their time:**  Keep your questions concise and to the point.\n*   **Email is an option, but in-person is often better:** Unless it's a quick clarifying question.\n\n**To help me give you even more specific advice, tell me:**\n\n*   **What kind of question are you trying to submit?** (e.g., technical question, customer service question, general knowledge question)\n*   **Where are you trying to submit it?** (e.g., a specific website, a forum, to a person)\n\nThe more details you provide, the better I can assist you!\n",
